    // The number 2 is the most frequent divisor for any sufficiently large range.
    // For any range [l, r], the count of multiples of d is floor(r/d) - floor((l-1)/d).
    // This count is maximized when d is minimized.
    // The smallest possible divisor (greater than 1) is 2.
    // So, 2 will always be the most frequent divisor, or tied for the most frequent.
    // The only exception is if the range [l, r] is very small and does not contain any multiple of 2,
    // but contains a multiple of some other number.
    // For example, if l=3, r=3. No multiple of 2. Multiple of 3 is 3. Answer is 3.
