#include <algorithm>
#include <iostream>
#include <vector>

int main() {
    std::ios_base::sync_with_stdio(false);
    std::cin.tie(NULL);
    int t;
    std::cin >> t;
    while (t--) {
        int n;
        std::cin >> n;
        std::vector<long long> a(2 * n);
        for (int i = 0; i < 2 * n; ++i) {
            std::cin >> a[i];
        }
        std::sort(a.begin(), a.end());
        // The problem asks for the minimum absolute difference between medians.
        // After sorting the entire array, the optimal strategy is to pick
        // the n-th element (0-indexed: a[n-1]) as the median for one class
        // and the (n+1)-th element (0-indexed: a[n]) as the median for the other class.
        // This is because if we sort all 2n elements, say a_1 <= a_2 <= ... <= a_{2n},
        // and we want to form two classes of odd sizes, say S1 and S2, such that S1+S2=2n.
        // The median of a class of size K (odd) is the (K+1)/2-th element.
        //
        // Consider the partition where one class takes elements from a_1 to a_n
        // and the other class takes elements from a_{n+1} to a_{2n}.
        // This is not a valid partition because the sizes are n.
        //
        // The key insight is that to minimize the difference between medians,
        // the medians themselves should be as close as possible in the sorted global list.
        //
        // Let the sorted array be A[0], A[1], ..., A[2n-1].
        //
        // Consider the case where one class has size 1 and the other has size 2n-1.
        // If class 1 has A[i] as its only member, its median is A[i].
        // The other class has 2n-1 members. Its median would be the n-th element
        // among its members.
        //
        // The problem statement implies that the minimum difference is always
        // achieved by taking a[n-1] and a[n] as the medians.
        //
        // Let's verify this.
        // Suppose we have two classes C1 and C2 with odd sizes S1 and S2.
        // Let m1 be the median of C1 and m2 be the median of C2.
        //
        // If we sort all 2n elements: a_0, a_1, ..., a_{2n-1}.
        // The median of a class of size K (odd) is the element at index (K-1)/2 if 0-indexed.
        //
        // The smallest possible median for any class is a_0 (if a class has size 1 and contains a_0).
        // The largest possible median for any class is a_{2n-1} (if a class has size 1 and contains a_{2n-1}).
        //
        // Consider the elements a_{n-1} and a_n.
        // We can always form a class C1 of size 1 containing a_{n-1}. Its median is a_{n-1}.
        // The remaining 2n-1 elements form C2. Its median will be the n-th element among them.
        // If a_{n-1} is removed, the elements are a_0, ..., a_{n-2}, a_n, ..., a_{2n-1}.
        // The n-th element (1-indexed) in this sequence is a_n.
        // So, we can have medians a_{n-1} and a_n. The difference is a_n - a_{n-1}.
        //
        // Is it possible to achieve a smaller difference?
        // Suppose there exists a partition with medians m1 and m2 such that |m1 - m2| < a_n - a_{n-1}.
        // This would imply that m1 and m2 must be "closer" than a_{n-1} and a_n.
        //
        // Any median of a class of odd size K must be one of the elements in the original array.
        //
        // The crucial observation is that if we sort the entire array,
        // the elements a[0], ..., a[n-1] are the 'smaller half' and a[n], ..., a[2n-1] are the 'larger half'.
        // To minimize the difference between medians, we want one median to be as small as possible
        // and the other as large as possible, but still close to each other.
        //
        // The smallest possible median for any class is a[0].
        // The largest possible median for any class is a[2n-1].
        //
        // Consider the elements a[n-1] and a[n].
        // a[n-1] is the largest element in the first half of the sorted array.
        // a[n] is the smallest element in the second half of the sorted array.
        //
        // It can be proven that any partition into two odd-sized classes will have one median
        // less than or equal to a[n-1] and the other greater than or equal to a[n].
        //
        // Let C1 and C2 be the two classes with sizes S1 and S2.
        // Let m1 be the median of C1 and m2 be the median of C2.
        //
        // Suppose m1 < a[n-1] and m2 < a[n]. This is not possible.
        // Suppose m1 > a[n-1] and m2 > a[n]. This is not possible.
        //
        // The total number of elements less than or equal to a[n-1] is at least n.
        // The total number of elements greater than or equal to a[n] is at least n.
        //
        // If m1 is the median of C1, then at least (S1+1)/2 elements in C1 are <= m1.
        // If m2 is the median of C2, then at least (S2+1)/2 elements in C2 are <= m2.
        //
        // The sum of elements less than or equal to a[n-1] is at least n.
        // The sum of elements greater than or equal to a[n] is at least n.
        //
        // It is a known result for this type of problem that the minimum difference
        // is achieved by taking the difference between the two middle elements
        // of the globally sorted array.
        //
        // For 2n elements, the middle elements are at indices n-1 and n (0-indexed).
        //
        // Example 1: n=1, a = [1, 1]. Sorted: [1, 1].
        // n-1 = 0, n = 1. a[0]=1, a[1]=1. Difference = |1-1|=0. Correct.
        //
        // Example 2: n=3, a = [6, 5, 4, 1, 2, 3]. Sorted: [1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6].
        // n-1 = 2, n = 3. a[2]=3, a[3]=4. Difference = |4-3|=1. Correct.
        //
        // Example 3: n=5, a = [13, 4, 20, 13, 2, 5, 8, 3, 17, 16].
        // Sorted: [2, 3, 4, 5, 8, 13, 13, 16, 17, 20].
        // n-1 = 4, n = 5. a[4]=8, a[5]=13. Difference = |13-8|=5. Correct.
        //
        // The logic seems to hold for all examples.
        // The minimum difference is simply a[n] - a[n-1].
        std::cout << a[n] - a[n - 1] << "\n";
    }
    return 0;
}

