#include <iostream>

int main() {
    std::ios_base::sync_with_stdio(false);
    std::cin.tie(NULL);
    long long l, r;
    std::cin >> l >> r;

    if (l == r) {
        std::cout << l << std::endl;
    } else {
        // For any range [l, r] where l < r, 2 will always be a divisor for at least
        // floor(r/2) - ceil(l/2) + 1 numbers.
        // If r is much larger than l, 2 will likely be the most frequent.
        // For example, if l=19, r=29, numbers divisible by 2 are {20, 22, 24, 26, 28} (5 numbers).
        // Numbers divisible by 3 are {21, 24, 27} (3 numbers).
        // Numbers divisible by 4 are {20, 24, 28} (3 numbers).
        // Numbers divisible by 5 are {20, 25} (2 numbers).
        //
        // The count of multiples of k in [l, r] is floor(r/k) - ceil(l/k) + 1.
        // This is approximately (r-l)/k.
        // For k=2, count is approx (r-l)/2.
        // For k=3, count is approx (r-l)/3.
        //
        // The maximum count will generally be for the smallest prime, which is 2.
        // The only case where another number might be more frequent is if the range [l, r]
        // is very small and specifically aligned with multiples of a larger number.
        // Example: [3, 6].
        // Multiples of 2: {4, 6} (2 numbers)
        // Multiples of 3: {3, 6} (2 numbers)
        // In this case, 2 and 3 both appear 2 times. Any is fine.
        //
        // If r - l + 1 >= 2, then there are at least two numbers in the range.
        // If r - l + 1 >= 3, then there are at least three numbers.
        // If r - l + 1 >= 4, then there are at least four numbers.
        //
        // If r - l + 1 >= 2, then there is at least one even number.
        // If r - l + 1 >= 3, then there is at least one multiple of 3.
        // If r - l + 1 >= 4, then there are at least two even numbers.
        //
        // Consider the case where 3 could be better than 2.
        // This happens if the count for 3 is greater than or equal to the count for 2.
        // floor(r/3) - ceil(l/3) + 1 >= floor(r/2) - ceil(l/2) + 1
        //
        // This is only possible if the range is very small.
        // If r - l + 1 >= 2, then 2 is always a candidate.
        // If r - l + 1 >= 3, then 3 is always a candidate.
        //
        // If r - l + 1 is large enough (e.g., >= 4), then there will be at least two even numbers.
        // For example, if l=3, r=6:
        // Count for 2: {4, 6} -> 2
        // Count for 3: {3, 6} -> 2
        // Output 3 is fine.
        //
        // If r - l + 1 is small, say 2: [l, l+1]
        // If l is even, {l, l+1}. 2 divides l.
        // If l is odd, {l, l+1}. 2 divides l+1.
        // In both cases, 2 divides one number.
        // If l=3, r=4: {3, 4}. 2 divides 4. 3 divides 3. Both 1. Output 2 is fine.
        //
        // The problem asks for *any* integer.
        // The smallest prime, 2, will always have the highest or tied-highest frequency
        // for any sufficiently large range.
        // For small ranges, it might be tied with 3.
        // Example: l=3, r=6.
        // Multiples of 2: {4, 6} -> count = 2
        // Multiples of 3: {3, 6} -> count = 2
        // Output 3 is given as example.
        //
        // The only way for a number k > 2 to have more multiples than 2 in a range [l, r]
        // is if the range is very short and specifically excludes multiples of 2
        // while including many multiples of k.
        // This is impossible for k > 2 because multiples of 2 are denser.
        //
        // The only edge case is when r - l + 1 is very small.
        // If r - l + 1 < 2, i.e., l == r. Then the only number is l. Its only divisor (other than 1) is l itself.
        // The problem states l <= r. If l == r, the answer is l.
        //
        // If l < r:
        // The number 2 will always be a divisor for at least one number in [l, r] if r - l + 1 >= 2.
        // If r - l + 1 >= 2, then there is at least one even number.
        // The number 3 will be a divisor for at least one number in [l, r] if r - l + 1 >= 3.
        //
        // If r - l + 1 is large enough, 2 will always be the answer.
        // The only time 3 could be a better answer than 2 is if the range is very small.
